WEBVTT

1
00:00:02.110 --> 00:00:04.800
There are lots of ways to make a decision. You

2
00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:09.360
could flip a coin, you could follow your heart, or

3
00:00:09.420 --> 00:00:11.940
you could just make a choice at random and hope

4
00:00:11.980 --> 00:00:16.450
for the best. That's probably okay for small decisions, but

5
00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:19.700
what about more important ones? It's better to think carefully

6
00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:22.300
about your options and consider the many paths you could

7
00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:25.260
take. With the right tools, you can learn to do

8
00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:27.900
this objectively so you can make decisions that you feel

9
00:00:27.980 --> 00:00:30.720
good about. Here are some strategies that can help.

10
00:00:32.910 --> 00:00:36.460
The first step to making any decision is simple: identify

11
00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:39.780
the problem. As an example, say you're trying to choose

12
00:00:39.800 --> 00:00:43.860
between two different apartments. One is cheaper but farther away

13
00:00:43.940 --> 00:00:47.860
from work. The other is closer and nicer, but much

14
00:00:47.920 --> 00:00:52.040
more expensive. Which one would you choose? Depending on what

15
00:00:52.060 --> 00:00:56.340
you value, you probably have some idea. This initial response,

16
00:00:56.380 --> 00:00:59.240
the one tied to your instincts and emotions, is perfectly

17
00:00:59.260 --> 00:01:02.200
valid. However, you should also try to look at your

18
00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:07.180
options rationally. Start by comparing them. There are

19
00:01:07.240 --> 00:01:10.400
several ways to do this. For example, you could list

20
00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:13.950
all the factors that you're considering, things like price, location,

21
00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:17.120
and other amenities. Then choose the one thing that's most

22
00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:20.550
important to you. With that in mind, which option comes

23
00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:24.680
out on top? You could go one step further and

24
00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:28.060
create a point system. Take that same list and turn

25
00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:31.540
it into a scorecard for each option. In this example,

26
00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:34.710
that means apartment one would score high on affordable rent,

27
00:01:35.020 --> 00:01:39.230
let's say a ten, but much lower on location. Apartment

28
00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:42.600
two would score about the opposite. Keep going down the

29
00:01:42.660 --> 00:01:45.570
list until you've scored every item, being as objective as

30
00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:49.640
you can. Then add up the totals, and maybe you

31
00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:53.760
have a winner. Looking at it another way, you could

32
00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:56.190
evaluate one option at a time with a list of

33
00:01:56.280 --> 00:01:59.700
pros and cons. It sounds simple, but sometimes it helps

34
00:01:59.740 --> 00:02:02.960
to write these things down. This time it's okay to

35
00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:06.700
be subjective. Certain factors can and should carry more weight

36
00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:09.620
than others. It's how you feel about them that counts,

37
00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:11.840
so be honest about what these things mean to you.

38
00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:17.109
Imagining possible outcomes might give you some perspective on the

39
00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:21.320
decision. Say you're thinking about adopting a dog. What do

40
00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.580
you think the consequences might be in a month? In

41
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:29.590
a year? How about several years from now? Making

42
00:02:29.660 --> 00:02:32.720
decisions can be a rollercoaster ride, especially when there are

43
00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:36.240
long-term consequences to think about. We can't see into the

44
00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:40.900
future, but we can try to be prepared. At this

45
00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:44.880
point, it's normal to feel overwhelmed, even stuck. With so

46
00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:46.920
much to consider, how do you know you're making the

47
00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:50.460
right choice? There are two more techniques that can help

48
00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:52.760
you fire up your brain and trick it into thinking

49
00:02:52.769 --> 00:02:56.480
differently. Try this one: the two-minute diversion.

50
00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:01.280
Distract yourself with a two-minute activity that you find moderately

51
00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:04.900
difficult. Maybe you like playing mobile games or solving math

52
00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:08.790
problems for fun. Whatever works for you. Believe it or

53
00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:12.660
not, you'll continue to process the decision unconsciously, according to

54
00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:16.859
brain imaging research by Carnegie Mellon University. This brief window

55
00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:20.240
of time helps you internalize important details so you can

56
00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:25.140
make better, more insightful decisions. Sometimes it helps

57
00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:28.420
to step outside yourself and pretend you're helping someone else.

58
00:03:29.280 --> 00:03:31.940
Studies show we're able to think more objectively in third

59
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.060
person. That's why it's easier to give advice than it

60
00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.500
is to receive it. If a friend or family member

61
00:03:38.540 --> 00:03:41.300
was struggling with the same decision, what questions would you

62
00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:45.930
ask them? What compromises would you suggest? Really think about

63
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:49.000
it. Adopting a different point of view might help you

64
00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:53.930
see the situation in a whole new way. Making decisions

65
00:03:54.020 --> 00:03:56.780
isn't like taking a test. There are no right or

66
00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.780
wrong answers per se. It just depends on the situation.

67
00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:03.220
Focus on taking the time to think about your options

68
00:04:03.340 --> 00:04:05.540
and what you hope to achieve so you can feel

69
00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:08.780
confident about the choices you make. It's not as easy

70
00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:12.120
as flipping a coin, but it's worth the extra effort.

71
00:04:19.399 --> 00:04:23.340
GCF Global, creating opportunities for a better life.
